# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arwad
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] Abdera shares its name with a city in Thrace and another in North Africa.
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] Its coins bore the inscription ʾbdrt (Punic: 𐤏𐤁𐤃𐤓𐤕).
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] The first element in the name appears to be the Punic word for "servant" or "slave"; the second element seems shared by the Phoenician names for Gadir (now Cadiz) and Cythera but of unclear meaning.
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] It appears in Greek sources as *tà Ábdēra* (Ancient Greek: τὰ Ἄβδηρα) and *Aúdēra* (Αὔδηρα), *Ábdara* (Ἄβδαρα), and *tò Ábdēron* (τὸ Ἄβδηρον).
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] Abdera was founded in the 8th century BCE as a Phoenician colony.
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] It became a Carthaginian trading station and, after a period of decline, became one of the more important towns in the Roman province of Hispania Baetica.
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] Tiberius seems to have made the place a Roman colony.
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] The most ancient coins bear its name with the head of Melqart and a tuna.
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] Coins from the time of Tiberius show the town's main temple with two erect tunas as its columns.
[src:arwad/abdera-spain] Early Roman coins were bilingual with Latin inscriptions on one side stating the name of the emperor and the town and with Punic text on the other side simply stating the name of the town.
[src:arwad/abyla] The name **Abyla** is said to have been a Punic name ("Lofty Mountain" or "Mountain of God") for Jebel Musa, the southern Pillar of Hercules.
[src:arwad/abyla] It appears in Greek variously as *Abýla* (Ἀβύλα), *Abýlē* (Ἀβύλη), *Ablýx* (Ἀβλύξ), and *Abílē Stḗlē* (Ἀβίλη Στήλη, "Pillar of Abyla") and in Latin as Mount Abyla (**Abyla Mons**) or the Pillar of Abyla (**Abyla Columna**).
[src:arwad/abyla] The settlement below Jebel Musa was later renamed for the seven hills around the site, collectively referred to as the "Seven Brothers" (Ancient Greek: Ἑπτάδελφοι, *Heptádelphoi*; Latin: *Septem Fratres*).
[src:arwad/abyla] In particular, the Roman stronghold at the site took the name "Fort at the Seven Brothers" (**Castellum ad Septem Fratres**).
[src:arwad/abyla] This was gradually shortened to Septem (Σέπτον, *Sépton*) or, occasionally, **Septa**.
[src:arwad/abyla] It continued as *Sebtan* or *Sabta* (Arabic: سبتة) during the Middle Ages.
[src:arwad/abyla] The Phoenicians found a small Berber settlement on the Strait of Gibraltar at Ceuta but, because the extremely narrow isthmus joining the Peninsula of Almina to the African mainland makes the site imminently defensible, they swiftly made it their own.
[src:arwad/abyla] Abyla was one of a number of settlements in the area—including Tinga (Tangiers), Kart (San Roque), and Gadir (Cádiz)—that helped the Phoenicians and Carthaginians control maritime trade between the Atlantic and the Mediterranean.
[src:arwad/abyla] After the fall of Carthage in the Punic Wars, most of northwest Africa was left to the Roman client states of Numidia and Mauretania but Punic culture continued to thrive in Septem, whose residents mostly continued to speak Punic into the reign of Augustus.
[src:arwad/abyla] Rome began exerting increasing control over the region, though, first through traders and advisors and then—particularly after Thapsus—through the incorporation of more and more towns and regions into directly administered provinces.
[src:arwad/abyla] Roman settlement at Septem began under Augustus.
[src:arwad/abyla] Caligula assassinated the Mauretanian king Ptolemy in AD 40 and seized his kingdom.
[src:arwad/abyla] Claudius organized the new territories in 42, placing Septem in the province of Mauretania Tingitana (administered from Tingis, present-day Tangiers) and raising it to the level of a colony, which gave Roman citizenship to its residents.
[src:arwad/abyla] Wealthy Romans from Claudius's and Nero's reigns are attested in funerary inscriptions found around the Septem basilica.
[src:arwad/abyla] Controlling commercial and military access to the Gibraltar Strait, Septem flourished under the empire.
[src:arwad/abyla] Around AD 100, under Trajan, a local senate was made organized from the local nobles (**ordo decurionum**).
[src:arwad/abyla] The town was particularly known for its salt and salted fish, which expanded greatly after about AD 140 as new production centers opened up around the town forum.
[src:arwad/abyla] The salt, salted fish, and salted produce were exported—mainly across the strait to Roman Spain—in jars manufactured around the city.
[src:arwad/abyla] Roman roads also connected it over land with Tingis and Volubilis, increasing inland trade and security from Berber raiding.
[src:arwad/abyla] By the 2nd century, romanization was nearly complete and Latin appears in most surviving inscriptions.
[src:arwad/abyla] Alongside the Roman colonists, however, there remained a sizable community of romanized Berbers whose primary tongue continued to be local dialects mixed with Punic and Latin loanwords; this eventually became African Romance.
[src:arwad/abyla] Around AD 200, the African emperor Septimius Severus included the town in some of the largesse with which he favored the region.
[src:arwad/abyla] The town's prosperity continued into the late 3rd century, after which production centers were abandoned and the use of money falls off.
[src:arwad/abyla] Septem was an important Christian center by the 4th century; one of the basilicas from this time has recently been rediscovered.) In the late 4th century, under Theodosius I, the city still had 10,000 inhabitants, nearly all Christian and Latin-speaking.
[src:arwad/abyla] By the time of Belisarius's reconquest of North Africa, the Vandals had already lost Septem to local Berber (**Mauri**) revolts.
[src:arwad/abyla] The Byzantines retook the entire coastline, then established their "Commander of Mauretania" (**Dux Mauretania**) at the more defensible Septem instead of the old capital at Tingis.
[src:arwad/abyla] Mauretania and the Byzantine holdings in Andalusia were nominally part of the Exarchate of Africa but so distant that it is likely the garrison at Septem was forced to do homage to Visigothic Spain.
[src:arwad/abyla] There are no reliable contemporary histories concerning the end of the Islamic conquest of the Maghreb around the year 710.
[src:arwad/abyla] Instead, the rapid Muslim conquest of Spain produced romances concerning Count Julian of Septem and his betrayal of Christendom in revenge for the dishonors that befell his daughter at the Visigothic court of King Roderick.
[src:arwad/abyla] After the death of Julian, sometimes also described as a king of the Ghomara Berbers, Berber converts to Islam took direct control of Septa.
[src:arwad/abyla] It was then destroyed during their great revolt against the Caliphate around 740.
[src:arwad/abyla] Septa subsequently remained a small village of Muslims and Christians surrounded by ruins until its resettlement in the 9th century by Mâjakas, chief of the Majkasa Berber tribe, who started the short-lived Banu Isam dynasty.
[src:arwad/abyla] The continuing existence of an embattled Christian community is attested by the martyrdom of St.
[src:arwad/abyla] Daniel Fasanella and his Franciscans in 1227; it subsequently survived until the town's capture by the Portuguese reëstablished the Roman Catholic Diocese of Ceuta on 4 April 1417.
[src:arwad/abyla] The Ceuta Cathedral was then raised on the site of old Septem's 6th-century church.
[src:arwad/achziv] Excavations have unearthed a fortified Canaanite city of the second millennium BCE.
[src:arwad/achziv] The Phoenician town of the first millennium BCE is known both from the Hebrew Bible and Assyrian sources.
[src:arwad/achziv] Phoenician Achzib went through ups and downs during the Persian and Hellenistic periods.
[src:arwad/achziv] In early Roman times the town, known as *Acdippa*, was a road station.
[src:arwad/achziv] The Bordeaux Pilgrim mentions it in 333–334 CE still as a road station; Jewish sources of the Byzantine period call it *Kheziv* and *Gesiv*.
[src:arwad/achziv] There is no information about settlement at the site for the early Muslim period.
[src:arwad/achziv] The Crusaders built a new village with a castle there.
[src:arwad/achziv] During the Mamluk and Ottoman periods a modest village occupied the old tell (archaeological mound).
[src:arwad/achziv] In modern times the site was known as the Palestinian town of Az-Zeeb, with a population of almost 2,000.
[src:arwad/achziv] It was depopulated during the Haganah's Operation Ben-Ami, on May 14, 1948, the last day of the British Mandate for Palestine.
[src:arwad/achziv] The sole permanent resident of Achziv since declaration of the State was Eli Avivi (1930–2018), an Israeli photographer and micronationalist who hosted visitors to the legally disputed micronation of "Akhzivland", a small stretch of beach where he lived since 1975 until his death.
[src:arwad/achziv] Mentioned in the Bible by its ancient name *Achzib*, evidence of human settlement at the site dates back to the 18th century BCE.
[src:arwad/achziv] During the Roman period (and in classical literature) the imperial authorities called it *Ecdippa*, *Ecdeppa*, or *Ecdippon*.
[src:arwad/achziv] By the early Middle Ages, the Arab name for the village "Az-Zeeb", or "al-Zib" (Arabic: الزيب meaning 'trickster') was locally in common usage.
[src:arwad/achziv] Az-Zeeb is a shortened form of the site's original ancient Canaanite/Phoenician name, *Achzib*.
[src:arwad/achziv] Human settlement at the site dates to as early as the 18th century BCE; and by the 10th century BCE it was a walled town.
[src:arwad/achziv] A tell excavated between 1941–44 and 1959-1964 found evidence of settlement from the Middle Bronze Age II, through the Roman Empire and the Early Middle Ages.
[src:arwad/achziv] Achziv was the first fortified settlement found at the site by archaeologists.
[src:arwad/achziv] In the Middle Bronze IIA (MBIIA), remains are found at Phase N5 with features including child burials in storage jars below floors.
[src:arwad/achziv] At the transition from MBIIA to MBIIB, the settlement was subject to a violent destruction.
[src:arwad/achziv] In the Middle Bronze IIB (MBIIB), Phase N4 was part of a large Canaanite port city.
[src:arwad/achziv] The massive ramparts, some 4.5 metres (15 feet) high, protected the city proper and a large area of port facilities.
[src:arwad/achziv] To the north and south the city extended to the two nearby rivers, which the Canaanite engineers connected by a fosse, thus transforming Achzib into an island.
[src:arwad/achziv] A substantial destruction level from the beginning of the Late Bronze Age proves that even these fortifications were eventually not sufficient.
[src:arwad/achziv] A fierce conflagration ended Phase N4 and led to the transition to the MBIIC/LBI in Phase N3.
[src:arwad/achziv] By the 1000 BCE, Achziv was a prosperous and fortified Phoenician town.
[src:arwad/achziv] Conquered by the Assyrian empire in the 8th century BCE, however, it was subsequently ruled by the Persians during the rule of the Roman Empire.
[src:arwad/achziv] Positioned on a passage between the plain of Acre and the city of Tyre, Achzib was an important road station.
[src:arwad/achziv] Between the 10th and 6th centuries BCE, it was a prosperous town, with public buildings and tombs with Phoenician inscriptions, attesting to the identity of its inhabitants at the time.
[src:arwad/achziv] Prior to the Assyrian invasion of Achziv under Sennacherib, in the late 8th-century BCE, Achziv and Akko belonged to the king of Sidon, and were considered Hittite territory.
[src:arwad/achziv] And the fifth lot came out for the tribe of the children of Asher ... and the outgoings thereof are at the sea from the coast to Achzib.
[src:arwad/achziv] Asher did not drive out the inhabitants of Acco, ... or of Achzib ...
[src:arwad/achziv] According to Biblical history, King David added the city into his Kingdom, but King Solomon returned it to Hiram I as part of the famous pact; archaeological evidence indicates that it remained Phoenician.
[src:arwad/achziv] During the reign of the Seleucids the border was established at Rosh HaNikra, just north to Achziv, making it a border city which they called *Ekdippa* (Έκδιππα in Ancient Greek) and put it under the control of Acre.
[src:arwad/achziv] Mentioned in the writings of Pseudo-Scylax, the site likely regained some importance in Hellenistic times.
[src:arwad/achziv] A maritime city named Cziv, nine miles (14 km) north of Acre, is mentioned by Josephus Flavius and later by Eusebius.
[src:arwad/achziv] Achziv (Cheziv) is mentioned in Jewish rabbinic writings, for example Midrash Vayikra Rabba 37:4.
[src:arwad/achziv] Additionally, Achziv is mentioned in the Babylonian Talmud, and by the relating Middle Age commentators, concerning the location of Achziv in regards to historical borders of Israel.
[src:arwad/achziv] At the end of the Roman era, a pottery workshop was located there.
[src:arwad/achziv] By the Early Middle Ages, Arab geographers were referring to the area as "az-Zeeb".
[src:arwad/achziv] With the arrival of the Crusaders and after the fall of Acre in 1104, "Casal Imbertia" or "Lambertie" was established there.
[src:arwad/achziv] During the Crusader era, it expanded and became the main centre of a large estate with the same name, Casal Imbert.
[src:arwad/achziv] Lefiegre, Le Quiebre and La Gabassie were all part of this estate.
[src:arwad/achziv] The site was commonly known as "*Casale Umberti*," or Casal Humberti (after Hubert of Pacy who held the casale), and it is documented in 1108.
[src:arwad/achziv] Az-Zeeb (meaning "trickster"), is first mentioned in Crusader sources in 1123 as a village belonging to Hubert of Pacy.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1146, the Crusaders established a settlement there protected by a castle and named "Casale Huberti" and sometimes still as "Casal Humberti".
[src:arwad/achziv] Under Baldwin III, European farmers settled there sometime before 1153.
[src:arwad/achziv] Arab geographer Ibn Jubayr toured Palestine in 1182 and mentioned az-Zeeb as a large fortress with a village and adjoining lands between Acre and Tyre.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1198, King Aimery gave a large part of the income from Az-Zeeb to the Teutonic Order.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1226, Arab geographer Yaqut al-Hamawi described az-Zeeb as a large village on the coast whose name was also pronounced "az-Zaib".
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1232 it was the site of the Battle of Casal Imbert between German and French Crusaders as part of the War of the Lombards.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1253 King Henry gave the whole estate of Casal Imbert to John of Ibelin.
[src:arwad/achziv] Shortly after, in 1256, John of Ibelin leased Az-Zeeb and all its dependant villages to the Teutonic Order for 10 years.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1261, the whole estate was sold to the Teutonic Order, in return for an annual sum for as long as Acre was in Christian hands.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1283 the village was mentioned as part of the domain of the Crusaders, according to the *hudna* (truce) between the Crusaders in Acre and the Mamluk sultan Qalawun.
[src:arwad/achziv] The Arab village of Az-Zeeb was established during the later Mamluk period with the houses erected using the stones of the destroyed Crusader castle; and thrived throughout the Ottoman rule.
[src:arwad/achziv] There are descriptions of the castle and village by Arab chroniclers in the 12th and 13th centuries, just prior to and during the rule of the Mamluks in the region.
[src:arwad/achziv] In the early 16th century, az-Zeeb was incorporated into the Ottoman Empire and its inhabitants cultivated various crops and raised livestock on which they paid taxes to the Ottoman authorities.
[src:arwad/achziv] According to the 1596 tax records, it was a village in the *nahiya* (subdistrict) of Akka, part of Sanjak Safad with a population of 132 households and 27 bachelors and an estimated total of 875 persons.
[src:arwad/achziv] The villagers paid a fixed tax rate of 25% on several agricultural items including, wheat, barley, "summer crops", fruits, cotton, beehives, goats, and water buffalo; a total of 23,669 akçe.
[src:arwad/achziv] A map by Pierre Jacotin from Napoleon's invasion of 1799 showed the village, named as *Zib*.
[src:arwad/achziv] British traveler James Silk Buckingham describes az-Zeeb in 1816 as a small town built on a hill near the sea with few palm trees rising above its houses.
[src:arwad/achziv] During the period of Egyptian rule in Palestine, the sheikh (chief) of az-Zeeb, Said al-Sabi, joined the 1834 peasants' rebellion against governor Ibrahim Pasha.
[src:arwad/achziv] He was arrested and exiled to Egypt by the authorities in the summer of that year because of his participation.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1875, when Victor Guérin visited, Az-Zeeb had 500 Muslim inhabitants.
[src:arwad/achziv] Guérin noted that the hill on which it was built had formerly been surrounded by a wall, traces of which were still to be seen on the east side.
[src:arwad/achziv] By the late 19th century, most of the village houses were built of stone, a mosque and a clinic had been established, and the residents cultivated olives, figs, mulberries, and pomegranates.
[src:arwad/achziv] The population consisted of about 400 Muslims.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1882, the Ottomans established an elementary school in az-Zeeb.
[src:arwad/achziv] A population list from about 1887 showed that Kh. ez Zib had about 730 inhabitants, all Muslim.
[src:arwad/achziv] Az-Zeeb became a part of the British Mandate of Palestine in 1922.
[src:arwad/achziv] In the 1922 census of Palestine, "*Al Zib*" had a population of 804; 803 Muslims and 1 Christian, where the one Christian was a Roman Catholic.
[src:arwad/achziv] The population had increased in the 1931 census to 1059, all Muslims, in a total of 251 houses.
[src:arwad/achziv] The main economic sectors in the village were in fishing and agriculture, particularly fruit cultivation, which included bananas, citrus, olives, and figs.
[src:arwad/achziv] The town held four olive presses: two mechanized and two animal-drawn.
[src:arwad/achziv] Between 1927 and 1945, the village's annual fish catch was 16 metric tons.
[src:arwad/achziv] In the 1945 statistics, the population of Az Zeeb was 1,910, all Muslims, with a total land area of 12,607 dunams.
[src:arwad/achziv] Of this, 2,973 dunams were used for citrus and bananas; 1,989 dunums were irrigated or used for orchards; 4,425 were for cereals; while 62 dunams were built-up (urban) areas.
[src:arwad/achziv] The population of the village in 1945 was 1,910.
[src:arwad/achziv] In 1946, the Jewish Resistance Movement attempted to blow up the railroad bridge over the creek at Achziv in an operation known as Night of the Bridges.
[src:arwad/achziv] A monument to the 14 soldiers killed there was erected on the site.
[src:arwad/achziv] Just before the official end to Mandate rule on May 14, 1948, and the start of the 1948 Arab–Israeli War, az-Zeeb was captured by the Haganah's Carmeli Brigade, being one of the main places targeted in Operation Ben-Ami.
[src:arwad/achziv] Morris writes that two Haganah companies reported in mid-May 1948 that they were "attacking al Zib with the aim of blowing up the village".
[src:arwad/achziv] Eyewitness accounts from among the villagers indicate that they mistook the incoming Israeli forces for Arab reinforcements because they had donned red and white *keffiyehs*, and that these forces quickly overwhelmed the local militia of 35–40 men.
[src:arwad/achziv] Many of the inhabitants fled to Lebanon or nearby villages, but many also remained in az-Zeeb until they were relocated by the Israeli authorities to the Arab coastal town of Mazra'a.
[src:arwad/achziv] Some villagers later claimed that the Haganah had "molested or violated" a number of women.
[src:arwad/achziv] The Israeli localities of Sa'ar and Gesher HaZiv were established on the village lands in 1948 and 1949.
[src:arwad/achziv] A domed mosque from the village has since been restored and serves as a tourist site, and the house of the last mukhtar (village headman) is now a museum.
[src:arwad/achziv] Today Achziv shores are part of the Achziv-Rosh haNikra marine protected area, which is located between the city of Naharia to the south and the Israeli-Lebanon border to the north.
[src:arwad/achziv] The marine protected area has 7 kilometers of shore line and continue into the sea for another 15 kilometers west.
[src:arwad/achziv] This marine nature reserve protects the fauna and flora of the stony reefs and the sandy beach environments.
[src:arwad/achziv] It is the only marine protected area in Israel in which the maximum depth is deeper than 850 meters.
[src:arwad/achziv] Near the national park is Akhzivland, founded by Eli Avivi in 1971 and currently used as a vacation village and camping site.
[src:arwad/achziv] Remnants of ancient Achziv, now known as Tel Achziv, are located on a sandstone mound between two streams, Kziv on the north and Shaal on the south, close to the border with Lebanon.
[src:arwad/achziv] An ancient port was located on the coast, and another secondary port is located 700 m to the south.
[src:arwad/achziv] Archeological excavations have revealed that a walled city existed at the location from the Middle Bronze period.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city occupies a strategic location, sitting in a natural harbour at the extremity of Haifa Bay on the coast of the Mediterranean's Levantine Sea.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Aside from coastal trading, it was an important waypoint on the region's coastal road and the road cutting inland along the Jezreel Valley.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The first settlement during the Early Bronze Age was abandoned after a few centuries but a large town was established during the Middle Bronze Age.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Continuously inhabited since then, it is among the oldest continuously inhabited settlements on Earth.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It has, however, been subject to conquest and destruction several times and survived as little more than a large village for centuries at a time.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre was a hugely important city during the Crusades as a maritime foothold on the Mediterranean coast of the southern Levant and was the site of several battles, including the 1189–1191 Siege of Acre and 1291 Siege of Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It was the last stronghold of the Crusaders in the Holy Land prior to that final battle in 1291.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] At the end of Crusader rule, the city was destroyed by the Mamluks, thereafter existing as a modest fishing village until the rule of Daher al-Umar in the 18th century.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 1947, Acre formed part of Mandatory Palestine and had a population of 13,665, of whom 10,930 were Muslim and 2,490 were Christian, and 105 were Jewish.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] As a result of the United Nations Partition Plan for Palestine and subsequent 1948 Arab–Israeli war, the population of the town dramatically changed as its Palestinian-Arab population was expelled or forced to flee; it was then resettled by Jewish immigrants.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In present-day Israel, the population was 52,885 in 2024, made up of Jews, Muslims, Christians, Druze, and Baháʼís.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In particular, Acre is the holiest city of the Baháʼí Faith in Israel and receives many pilgrims of that faith every year.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre is one of Israel's mixed cities; 32% of the city's population is Arab.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Old City of Acre is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The ultimate etymology of the name is unknown. but appears to be Northwest Semitic.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre is first recorded in Egyptian hieroglyphs in the execration texts c.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] 1800 BC by the name *ʿky*, reconstructed by Anson F.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Amarna letters also mention an **Akka** in the mid-14th century BC, and Shmuel Aḥituv gives the Canaanite form as **ʿAkā*.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Akkadian form **Akku** appears in the 7th century, and in the Hebrew Bible, the name is עַכּוֹ **ʻAkkō**.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] This long ā to long ō transition has been interpreted as evidence of the Canaanite shift.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It was, however, not universally applied, as several scholars note the final ā form persisted well into the first half of the 1st millennium CE, and a Jewish Palestinian Aramaic form עכה with a final long ā was also extant.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre was known to the Greeks as **Ákē** (Ancient Greek: Ἄκη), a homonym for a Greek word meaning "cure".
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Greek legend then offered a folk etymology that Hercules had found curative herbs at the site after one of his many fights.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] This name was Latinized as **Ace** or **Acce** (used by Pliny).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Under the Diadochi, the Ptolemaic Kingdom renamed the city **Ptolemaïs** and the Seleucid Empire called it **Antioch**.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] As both names were shared by a great many other towns, they were variously distinguished.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Syrians called it "Antioch in Ptolemais" (Ἀντιόχεια τῆς ἐν Πτολεμαΐδι, *Antiókheia tês en Ptolemaΐdi*).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Under Claudius, it was also briefly known as **Germanicia in Ptolemais** (Γερμανίκεια τῆς ἐν Πτολεμαΐδι, *Germaníkeia tês en Ptolemaΐdi*).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] As a Roman colony, it was notionally refounded and renamed **Colonia Claudii Caesaris Ptolemais** or **Colonia Claudia Felix Ptolemais Garmanica Stabilis** after its imperial sponsor Claudius; it was known as **Colonia Ptolemais** for short.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre's original West Semitic place name is preserved in the Arabic form **Akka** (عكا), and was revived as the city's official name again following the Muslim conquest of Syria, as one of the cities of Jund al-Urdunn.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It was in the Crusader States' Kingdom of Jerusalem that the 'r' was inserted into its Latin name, becoming **Acre**.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The name **Saint-Jean-d'Acre** (Modern French: *Saint-Jean-d'Acre* [sɛ̃ ʒɑ̃ dakʁ]) used for the Knights Hospitaller's headquarters in the city, came to used for the city itself during this period.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] This name remained quite popular in the Christian world until modern times, often translated into the language being used: *Saint John of Acre* (in English), **San Juan de Acre** (in Spanish), **Sant Joan d'Acre** (in Catalan), **San Giovanni d'Acri** (in Italian), etc.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre lies at the northern end of a wide bay with Mount Carmel at the south.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It is the best natural roadstead on the southern Phoenician coast and has easy access to the Valley of Jezreel.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It was settled early and has always been important for the fleets of kingdoms and empires contesting the area, serving as the main port for the entire southern Levant up to the modern era.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The ancient town was located atop Tel ʿAkkō (Hebrew) or Tell al-Fuḫḫār (Arabic, Tel el-Foukhar, meaning "tell of the clay/sherds"), 1.5 km (0.93 mi) east of the present city and 800 m (2,600 ft) north of the Na'aman River.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In antiquity, however, it formed an easily protected peninsula directly beside the former mouth of the Na'aman or Belus.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The earliest discovered settlement dates to around 3000 BC during the Early Bronze Age, but appears to have been abandoned after a few centuries, possibly because of inundation of its surrounding farmland by the Mediterranean.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre was resettled as an urban centre during the Middle Bronze Age (MBA, c.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] 2000–1550 BC) and has been continuously inhabited since then.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Egyptian execration texts record one 18th-century ruler as Tūra-ʿAmmu (Tꜣʿmw).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Further to the north was the important MBA site of Tel Kabri dominating the Akko plain.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre was listed as "Aak" among the conquests of the Egyptian pharaoh Thutmose III.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] 1350 BC), there was turmoil in Egypt's Levantine provinces.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Amarna Archive contains letters concerning the ruler(s) of Acco.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In one, King Biridiya of Megiddo complains to Amenhotep III or Akhenaten about the king of Acre, whom he accuses of treason for releasing the captured Hapiru king Labaya of Shechem instead of delivering him to Egypt.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Excavations of Tel ʿAkkō have shown that this period of Acre involved industrial production of pottery, metal, and other trade goods.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre continued as a Phoenician city and was referenced as a Phoenician city by the Assyrians.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Josephus, however, claimed it as a province of the Kingdom of Israel under Solomon.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Around 725 BC, Acre joined Sidon and Tyre in a revolt against the Neo-Assyrian emperor Shalmaneser V.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] There is a clear destruction layer in the ruins, probably dating to the 7th century BC.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre served as a major port of the Persian Empire, with Strabo noting its importance in campaigns against the Egyptians.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] According to Strabo and Diodorus Siculus, Cambyses II attacked Egypt after massing a huge army on the plains near the city of Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Persians expanded the town westward and probably improved its harbor and defenses.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In December 2018, archaeologists digging at the site of Tell Keisan in Acre unearthed the remains of a Persian military outpost that might have played a role in the successful 525 BC Achaemenid invasion of Egypt.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city's industrial production continued into the late Persian era, with particularly expanded iron works.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Persian-period fortifications at Tell Keisan were later heavily damaged during Alexander's fourth-century BC campaign to drive the Achaemenids out of the Levant.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] After Alexander's death, his main generals divided his empire among themselves.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] At first, the Egyptian Ptolemies held the land around Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Ptolemy II renamed the city Ptolemais in his own and his father's honour in the 260s BC.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Antiochus III conquered the town for the Syrian Seleucids in 200 BC.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the late 170s or early 160s BC, Antiochus IV founded a Greek colony in the town, which he named Antioch after himself.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] About 165 BC Judas Maccabeus defeated the Seleucids in several battles in Galilee, and drove them into Ptolemais.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] About 153 BC Alexander Balas, son of Antiochus IV Epiphanes, contesting the Seleucid crown with Demetrius, seized the city, which opened its gates to him.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Demetrius offered many bribes to the Maccabees to obtain Jewish support against his rival, including the revenues of Ptolemais for the benefit of the Temple in Jerusalem, but in vain.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Jonathan Apphus threw in his lot with Alexander; Alexander and Demetrius met in battle and the latter was killed.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 150 BC Alexander received Jonathan with great honour in Ptolemais.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Some years later, however, Tryphon, an officer of the Seleucid Empire, who had grown suspicious of the Maccabees, enticed Jonathan into Ptolemais and there treacherously took him prisoner.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city was captured by Alexander Jannaeus (ruled c.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Around 37 BC, the Romans conquered the Hellenized Phoenician port-city called Akko.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It became a colony in southern Roman Phoenicia, called *Colonia Claudia Felix Ptolemais Garmanica Stabilis*.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Ptolemais stayed Roman for nearly seven centuries until 636 AD, when it was conquered by the Muslim Arabs.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Under Augustus, a gymnasium was built in the city.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 4 BC, the Roman proconsul Publius Quinctilius Varus assembled his army there in order to suppress the revolts that broke out in the region following the death of Herod the Great.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] During the rule of the emperor Claudius there was a building drive in Ptolemais and veterans of the legions settled here.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city was one of four colonies (with Berytus, Aelia Capitolina and Caesarea Maritima) created in the ancient Levant by Roman emperors for Roman veterans.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] During the Great Jewish Revolt (66–73 CE), Acre functioned as a staging point for both Cestius's and Vespasian's campaigns to suppress the revolt in Judaea.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] An important Roman colony (**colonia**) was established at the city that greatly increased the control of the region by the Romans over the next century with Roman colonists translated there from Italy.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Romans enlarged the port and the city grew to more than 20,000 inhabitants in the second century under emperor Hadrian.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Ptolemais greatly flourished for two more centuries.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] After the permanent division of the Roman Empire in 395 AD, Ptolemais was administered by the successor state, the Byzantine Empire.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city started to lose importance and in the seventh century was reduced to a small settlement of less than one thousand inhabitants.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Following the defeat of the Byzantine army of Heraclius by the Rashidun army of Khalid ibn al-Walid in the Battle of Yarmouk, and the capitulation of the Christian city of Jerusalem to the Caliph Umar, Acre came under the rule of the Rashidun Caliphate beginning in 638.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] According to the early Muslim chronicler al-Baladhuri, the actual conquest of Acre was led by Shurahbil ibn Hasana, and it likely surrendered without resistance.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Arab conquest brought a revival to the town of Acre, and it served as the main port of Palestine through the Umayyad and Abbasid Caliphates that followed, and through Crusader rule into the 13th century.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The first Umayyad caliph, Muawiyah I (r.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] 661–680), regarded the coastal towns of the Levant as strategically important.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Thus, he strengthened Acre's fortifications and settled Persians from other parts of Muslim Syria to inhabit the city.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] From Acre, which became one of the region's most important dockyards along with Tyre, Mu'awiyah launched an attack against Byzantine-held Cyprus.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Byzantines assaulted the coastal cities in 669, prompting Mu'awiyah to assemble and send shipbuilders and carpenters to Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The 9th-century historian Ahmad Ibn Yahya al-Baladhuri in his book *Kitab Futuh al-Buldan*, notes that both Akka and Sur (Tyre) were rebuilt by 'Abd al-Malik ibn-Marwan (r.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] 685-705) after having "fallen into ruins", presumably as a result of the Byzantine assaults.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] He also notes that when Syrian sheikhs came to reside in Akka and Sur and other cities along the coast of Syria, there were Arab troops and Greeks already there, who over time were joined by people from other regions too.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city continued to serve as the principal naval base of Jund al-Urdunn ("Military District of Jordan") until the reign of Caliph Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik (723–743), who moved the bulk of the shipyards north to Tyre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the early Abbasid period, Caliph al-Mutawakkil developed Acre into a major naval base in 861, equipping the city with battleships and combat troops.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Palestinian Jerusalemite geographer Al-Maqdisi (c.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] 945-991) writes of Akka that it was unforitifed, unlike Sur/Tyre, until fortifications were built by the autonomous Emir Ibn Tulun of Egypt, who annexed the city in the 870s, and provided relative safety for merchant ships arriving at the city's port.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] During the 10th century, Acre was still part of Jund al-Urdunn, whose capital was at Tabariyya.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Al-Maqdisi visited Akka during the rule of the early Fatimid Caliphate in 985, describing a fortified coastal city with a large mosque possessing a substantial olive grove.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] When Persian traveller Nasir Khusraw visited Acre in 1047, he noted that the city was partially located on an elevation along the sea coast, citing the proclivity of inhabitants of the area to build along the sea only where there was higher ground, in fear of the waves encroachment.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] This figure indicates that Acre at that time was larger than its current Old City area, most of which was built between the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] After four years, the siege of Acre was successfully completed in 1104, with the city capitulating to the forces of King Baldwin I of Jerusalem following the First Crusade.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Crusaders made the town their chief port in the Kingdom of Jerusalem.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] On the first Crusade, Fulcher relates his travels with the Crusading armies of King Baldwin, including initially staying over in Acre before the army's advance to Jerusalem.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] This demonstrates that even from the beginning, Acre was an important link between the Crusaders and their advance into the Levant.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Its function was to provide Crusaders with a foothold in the region and access to vibrant trade that made them prosperous, especially giving them access to the Asiatic spice trade.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] By the 1130s it had a population of around 25,000 and was only matched for size in the Crusader kingdom by the city of Jerusalem.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Around 1170 it became the main port of the eastern Mediterranean, and the kingdom of Jerusalem was regarded in the west as enormously wealthy above all because of Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] According to an English contemporary, it provided more for the Crusader crown than the total revenues of the king of England.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the late 12th century, Jewish explorer Benjamin of Tudela recorded around 200 Jewish families in Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Its commercial prominence under Crusader rule seems to have attracted Jewish immigrants, including scholars from Europe.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] By the late 13th century, sources suggest that the Jewish community in Acre may have accumulated enough wealth to own slaves.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Andalusian geographer Ibn Jubayr wrote that in 1185 there was still a Muslim community in the city who worshipped in a small mosque.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre, along with Beirut and Sidon, capitulated without a fight to the Ayyubid sultan Saladin in 1187, after his decisive victory at Hattin and the subsequent Muslim capture of Jerusalem.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre remained in Muslim hands until it was unexpectedly besieged by King Guy of Lusignan—reinforced by Pisan naval and ground forces—in August 1189.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The siege was unique in the history of the Crusades since the Frankish besiegers were themselves besieged, by Saladin's troops.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It was not captured until July 1191 when the forces of the Third Crusade, led by King Richard I of England and King Philip II of France, came to King Guy's aid.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre then served as the *de facto* capital of the remnant Kingdom of Jerusalem in 1192.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] During the siege, German merchants from Lübeck and Bremen had founded a field hospital, which became the nucleus of the chivalric Teutonic Order.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Upon the Sixth Crusade, the city was placed under the administration of the Knights Hospitaller military order.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre continued to prosper as major commercial hub of the eastern Mediterranean, but also underwent turbulent times due to the bitter infighting among the Crusader factions that occasionally resulted in civil wars.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 1232, as a result of the inter-Christian War of the Lombards between the local barons and Emperor Frederick II, Acre organised itself as a commune under the mayorship of John of Ibelin.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The old part of the city, where the port and fortified city were located, protrudes from the coastline, exposing both sides of the narrow piece of land to the sea.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] This could maximize its efficiency as a port, and the narrow entrance to this protrusion served as a natural and easy defense to the city.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Both the archaeological record and Crusader texts emphasize Acre's strategic importance—a city in which it was crucial to pass through, control, and, as evidenced by the massive walls, protect.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre was the final major stronghold of the Crusader states when much of the Levantine coastline was conquered by Mamluk forces.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre itself fell to Sultan Al-Ashraf Khalil in 1291.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre, having been isolated and largely abandoned by Europe, was conquered by Mamluk sultan al-Ashraf Khalil in a bloody siege in 1291.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In line with Mamluk policy regarding the coastal cities (to prevent their future utilization by Crusader forces), Acre was entirely destroyed, with the exception of a few religious edifices considered sacred by the Muslims, namely the Nabi Salih tomb and the Ayn Bakar spring.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The destruction of the city led to popular Arabic sayings in the region enshrining its past glory.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 1321 the Syrian geographer Abu'l-Fida wrote that Acre was "a beautiful city" but still in ruins following its capture by the Mamluks.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Nonetheless, the "spacious" port was still in use and the city was full of artisans.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Throughout the Mamluk era (1260–1517), Acre was succeeded by Safed as the principal city of its province.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Incorporated into the Ottoman Empire in 1517, it appeared in the census of 1596, located in the *Nahiya* of Acca of the *Liwa* of Safad.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The population was 81 households and 15 bachelors, all Muslim.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] They paid a fixed tax-rate of 25% on agricultural products, including wheat, barley, cotton, goats, and beehives, water buffaloes, in addition to occasional revenues and market toll, a total of 20,500 Akçe.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] English academic Henry Maundrell in 1697 found it a ruin, save for a *khan* (caravanserai) built and occupied by French merchants for their use, a mosque and a few poor cottages.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The *khan* was named Khan al-Ilfranj after its French founders.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] During Ottoman rule, Acre continued to play an important role in the region via smaller autonomous sheikhdoms.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Towards the end of the 18th century Acre revived under the rule of Daher al-Umar, the Arab ruler of the Galilee, who made the city capital of his autonomous sheikhdom.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Daher rebuilt Acre's fortifications, using materials from the city's medieval ruins.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] He died outside its walls during an offensive against him by the Ottoman state in 1775.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Umar's successor, Jazzar Pasha, further fortified its walls when he virtually moved the capital of the Saida Eyelet ("Province of Sidon") to Acre where he resided.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Jazzar's improvements were accomplished through heavy imposts secured for himself all the benefits derived from his improvements.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] About 1780, Jazzar peremptorily banished the French trading colony, in spite of protests from the French government, and refused to receive a consul.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Both Daher and Jazzar undertook ambitious architectural projects in the city, building several caravanserais, mosques, public baths and other structures.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Some of the notable works included the Al-Jazzar Mosque, which was built out of stones from the ancient ruins of Caesarea and Atlit and the Khan al-Umdan, both built on Jazzar's orders.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Under Jazzar, Acre thrived, becoming the third largest city in Ottoman Syria.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Its population, then largely composed of migrants drawn by its burgeoning development, is estimated at twenty thousand.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 1799 Napoleon, in pursuance of his scheme for raising a Syrian rebellion against Turkish domination, appeared before Acre, but after a siege of two months (March–May) was repulsed by the Turks, aided by Sir Sidney Smith and a force of British sailors.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Having lost his siege cannons to Smith, Napoleon attempted to lay siege to the walled city defended by Ottoman troops on 20 March 1799, using only his infantry and small-calibre cannons, a strategy which failed, leading to his retreat two months later on 21 May.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Jazzar was succeeded on his death by his *mamluk*, Sulayman Pasha al-Adil, under whose milder rule the town advanced in prosperity till his death in 1819.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] After his death, Haim Farhi, who was his adviser, paid a huge sum in bribes to assure that Abdullah Pasha (son of Ali Pasha, the deputy of Sulayman Pasha), whom he had known from youth, will be appointed as ruler—which didn't stop the new ruler from assassinating Farhi.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Abdullah Pasha ruled Acre until 1831, when Ibrahim Pasha besieged and reduced the town and destroyed its buildings.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] During the Oriental Crisis of 1840, the city was bombarded on 4 November 1840 by the allied British, Austrian, and French squadrons, and, in the following year, it was restored to Turkish rule.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It regained some of its former prosperity after linking with the Hejaz Railway by a branch line from Haifa in 1913.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] According to the Ottoman population statistics of 1914, Akka had a total population of 40,852 people, consisting of 31,800 Muslims, 4,316 Catholic Greeks, 3,959 Orthodox Greeks, 332 Protestants, 268 Latins, 106 Jews, 67 Maronites and 4 Armenians.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It was the capital of the Akka Sanjak in the Beirut Vilayet until the British captured the city on 23 September 1918 during World War I.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] At the beginning of the Mandate period, in the 1922 census of Palestine, Acre had 6,420 residents: 4,883 of whom were Muslim; 1,344 Christian; 102 Baháʼí; 78 Jewish and 13 Druze.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the 1945 census Acre's population numbered 12,360; 9,890 Muslims, 2,330 Christians, 50 Jews and 90 classified as "other".
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre's fort was converted into a jail, where members of the Jewish underground were held during their struggle against the Mandate authorities, among them Ze'ev Jabotinsky, Shlomo Ben-Yosef, and Dov Gruner.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Gruner and Ben-Yosef were executed there.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Other Jewish inmates were freed by members of the Irgun, who broke into the jail on 4 May 1947 and succeeded in releasing Jewish underground movement activists.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the 1947 United Nations Partition Plan for Palestine, Acre was designated part of a future Arab state.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] On 18 March 4 technicians from the Palestine Electric Company and five British soldiers in their escort were killed while travelling to mend a cable in an RAF camp, when an Arab ambush exploded a mine on the route just outside the Moslem cemetery east of Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Haganah responded by blowing up a bridge outside the city and derailing a train.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] At some time in late April or early May 1948, Jewish forces cut the town's electricity supply responsible for pumping water, and a typhoid epidemic broke out.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Israeli officials later credited the facility with which they conquered the town in part to the effects of the demoralization induced by the epidemic.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Israel's Carmeli forces attacked on May 16 and, after an ultimatum was delivered that, unless the inhabitants surrendered, 'we will destroy you to the last man and utterly,' the town notables signed an instrument of surrender on the night between 17 and 18 May 1948.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Sixty (60) bodies were found and about three-quarters of the Arab population of the city (13,510 of 17,395) were displaced.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Throughout the 1950s, many Jewish neighbourhoods were established at the northern and eastern parts of the city, as it became a development town, designated to absorb numerous Jewish immigrants, largely Jews from Morocco.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The first Jewish mayor of Akko was Baruch Noy.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] He devoted himself to organizing the municipal services and worked to improve the situation of new immigrants and Arab residents.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] To promote coexistence in the City, Noy encouraged Arabs to run for municipal council and instituted the practice of electing a deputy mayor from the Arab inhabitants.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] During his term, the first new neighborhoods were established, and the beginning of the development of **Kfar Ata** was laid.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The old city of Akko remained largely Arab Muslim (including several Bedouin families), with an Arab Christian neighbourhood in close proximity.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city also attracted worshippers of the Baháʼí Faith, some of whom became permanent residents in the city, where the Baháʼí Mansion of Bahjí is located.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre has also served as a base for important events in Baháʼí history, including being the birthplace of Shoghi Effendi, and the short-lived schism between Baháʼís initiated by the attacks by Mírzá Muhammad ʻAlí against ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Baháʼís have since commemorated various events that have occurred in the city, including the imprisonment of Baháʼu'lláh.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the 1990s, the city absorbed thousands of Jews who immigrated from the former Soviet Union.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Within several years, however, the population balance between Jews and Arabs shifted backwards, as northern neighbourhoods were abandoned by many of its Jewish residents in favour of new housing projects in nearby Nahariya, while many Muslim Arabs moved in (largely coming from nearby Arab villages).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Nevertheless, the city still has a clear Jewish majority; in 2011, the population of 46,000 included 30,000 Jews and 14,000 Arabs.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Ethnic tensions erupted in the city on 8 October 2008 after an Arab citizen drove through a predominantly Jewish neighbourhood during Yom Kippur, leading to five days of violence between Arabs and Jews.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 2009, the population of Acre reached 46,300.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 2018 Shimon Lankri was re-elected mayor with 85% of the vote.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 2012, archaeologists excavating at the foot of the city's southern seawall found a quay and other evidence of a 2,300-year old port.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Mooring stones weighing 250–300 kilograms each were unearthed at the edge of a 5-meter long stone platform chiseled in Phoenician-style, thought to be an installation that helped raise military vessels from the water onto the shore.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Under the citadel and prison of Acre, archaeological excavations revealed a complex of halls, which was built and used by the Knights Hospitaller.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The current city level is 8 meters above the Crusader era, placing the fortress deep underground.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] This complex was a part of the Hospitallers' citadel, which was combined in the northern wall of Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The complex includes six semi-joined halls, one recently excavated large hall, a dungeon, a refectory (dining hall) and remains of an ancient Gothic church.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The fortress also comprises four wings surrounding an open Courtyard spanning 1,200 m².
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the northern part is a 4-meter-deep well.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Two plastered pools, likely for drinking water (northern) and washing (southern), are also present.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The courtyard is surrounded by arches supporting stairs to an upper level.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The northern wing, parallel to the city's northern walls, played a main defensive role, housing nine long halls across two floors used as warehouses and a rainwater reservoir fed from the fortress roof.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] These halls feature 10-meter-high barrel vaults, with external stone walls 3.5 meters thick.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Sugar Refinery Hall was a three-story building, with a large rainwater reservoir on the lower level comprising two connected 7.5-meter-high pools.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The main hall above, 7 meters high, contained hundreds of clay vessels used for sugar production, giving the hall its name.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Remnants of a tower, gate, and sewage channel remain on the northern side.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The western wing, partially excavated, appears to have two floors with 30 residential rooms per level.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] One feature is the Columned Hall, a 10-meter-long dining hall with a ribbed vault supported by three 3-meter-diameter stone columns.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The eastern wing includes unexcavated kitchen areas, while the Pillar Hall, a 35×40-meter chamber covering 1,400 m², has a cross-vaulted ceiling on square pillars, used for knightly meetings and ceremonies.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The southern wing forms a city street with a stone gate, featuring rare Crusader heraldic symbols.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] A vaulted hall with three rounded columns lies nearby.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] A marked tourist route leads to the Hospitaller chapter house, a narrow corridor to the refectory or crypt, and steep stairs to a long, narrow passage of unknown purpose connecting to the Crusader hospital.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Some underground areas are periodically closed for ongoing archaeological work.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Medieval European remains include the Church of Saint George and adjacent houses at the Genovese Square (Kikar ha-Genovezim or Kikar Genoa in Hebrew).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] There were also residential quarters and marketplaces run by merchants from Pisa and Amalfi in Crusader and medieval Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In March 2017, marine archaeologists from Haifa University announced the discovery of the wreck of a crusader ship with treasure dating back to 1062–1250 AD.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Excavators teams also unearthed ceramic bowls and jugs from places as Syria, Cyprus and southern Italy.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The researchers thought the golden coins could be used as a bribe to boat owners in hopes of buying their escape.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Robert Kool of the IAA identified these 30 coins as florins.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Acre has a Mediterranean climate (Köppen: *Csa*).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Today there are roughly 48,000 people who live in Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Among Israeli cities, Acre has a relatively high proportion of non-Jewish residents, with 32% of the population being Arab.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 2000, 95% of the residents in the Old City were Arab.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Only about 15% of the current Arab population in the city descends from families who lived there before 1948.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 2022, 56.5% of the population was Jewish, 29.5% was Muslim, 2.7% was Christian, 0.2% was Druze and 11.1% was counted as other.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] It is the holiest city of the Baháʼí Faith and receives many pilgrims every year.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 1999, there were 22 schools in Acre with an enrollment of 15,000 children.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Acre central bus station, served by Egged and Nateev Express, offers intra-city and inter-city bus routes to destinations all over Israel.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Nateev Express is currently contracted to provide the intra-city bus routes within Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city is also served by the Acre Railway Station, which is on the main Coastal railway line to Nahariya, with southerly trains to Beersheba and Modi'in-Maccabim-Re'ut.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Sir Charles Clore Jewish-Arab Community Centre in the Kiryat Wolfson neighbourhood runs youth clubs and programs for Jewish and Arab children.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 1990, Mohammed Faheli, an Arab resident of Acre, founded the Acre Jewish-Arab association, which originally operated out of two bomb shelters.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In 1993, Dame Vivien Duffield of the Clore Foundation donated funds for a new building.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Among the programs offered is Peace Child Israel, which employs theatre and the arts to teach coexistence.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The participants, Jews and Arabs, spend two months studying conflict resolution and then work together to produce an original theatrical performance that addresses the issues they have explored.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Another program is Patriots of Acre, a community responsibility and youth tourism program that teaches children to become ambassadors for their city.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the summer, the centre runs an Arab-Jewish summer camp for 120 disadvantaged children aged 5–11.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Some 1,000 children take part in the Acre Centre's youth club and youth programming every week.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Adult education programs have been developed for Arab women interested in completing their high school education and acquiring computer skills to prepare for joining the workforce.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The centre also offers parenting courses, and music and dance classes.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The Acco Festival of Alternative Israeli Theatre is an annual event that takes place in October, coinciding with the holiday of Sukkot.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The festival, inaugurated in 1979, provides a forum for non-conventional theatre, attracting local and overseas theatre companies.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Theatre performances by Jewish and Arab producers are staged at indoor and outdoor venues around the city.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] The city's football team, Hapoel Acre F.C., is a member of the Israeli Premier League, the top tier of Israeli football.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] They play in the Acre Municipal Stadium which was opened in September 2011.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] At the end of the 2008–2009 season, the club finished in the top five, and was promoted to the top tier for a second time, after an absence of 31 years.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] In the past the city was also home to Maccabi Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] However, the club was relocated to nearby Kiryat Ata and was renamed Maccabi Ironi Kiryat Ata.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Other current active clubs are Ahi Acre and the newly formed Maccabi Ironi Acre, both playing in Liga Bet.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p01] Both clubs also host their matches in the Acre Municipal Stadium.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Acre's Old City has been designated by UNESCO as a World Heritage Site.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Since the 1990s, large-scale archaeological excavations have been undertaken, overseen by the Old Acre Development Company Ltd., established in 1967, and efforts are being made to preserve ancient sites, coordinated under the Israel Ministry of Tourism.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The company collaborates with municipal authorities, acting as a government agency to supervise public and private construction in the Old City and advise on development matters.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In 2009, renovations were planned for Khan al-Umdan, the "Inn of the Columns," the largest of several Ottoman inns still standing in Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] It was built near the port at the end of the 18th century by Jazzar Pasha.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Merchants who arrived at the port would unload their wares on the first floor and sleep in lodgings on the second floor.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In 1906, a clock tower was added over the main entrance marking the 25th anniversary of the reign of the Turkish sultan, Abdul Hamid II.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Acre's fortification system was developed over centuries.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] During the Crusades, the Old City was larger, with different wall alignments.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In 1750, Daher al-Umar, the ruler of Acre, utilized the remnants of the Crusader walls as a foundation for his walls.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Two gates were set in the wall, the "land gate" in the eastern wall, and the "sea gate" in the southern wall.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The walls were reinforced between 1775 and 1799 by Jazzar Pasha and survived Napoleon's siege.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The wall was thin, at only 1.5 metres (4.9 ft), and rose to a height of between 10 metres (33 ft) and 13 metres (43 ft).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] A heavy land defensive wall was built north and east to the city in 1800–1814 by Jazzar Pasha and his Jewish advisor, Haim Farhi.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] It consists of a modern counter-artillery fortification which includes a thick defensive wall, a dry moat, cannon outposts and three *burges* (large defensive towers).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Since then, no major modifications have taken place.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The sea wall, which remains mostly complete, is the original wall built by Daher that was reinforced by Jazzar Pasha.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In 1910, two additional gates were set in the walls, one in the northern wall and one in the north-western corner of the city.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The city walls begin at the northwestern corner of the Old City at the Vineyard Tower (Arabic: *Burj al-Kurayim*, also known as the British Fortress).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] East of it, a new passage was created for Hagana Street.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The walls extend eastward, passing north of the citadel's fortifications and reaching a second new passage for Haim Weizmann Street.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Beyond this, the walls pass north of the arsenal and reach the Commander's Tower (Arabic: *Burj al-Kumandar*), a squat defensive bastion with multiple artillery positions guarding the northeastern corner of Acre's Old City.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] From its summit, there is a view of Haifa Bay and Mount Carmel above Haifa.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Nearby is the Treasures in the Walls Museum, showcasing the city's historical heritage with hundreds of artifacts, including furniture, textiles, and artistic and religious vessels.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The walls then turn south, where stairs lead to a promenade with cannons from the Napoleonic era.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The third defensive tower, the Gate Tower (Arabic: *Kapu Burj*), guarded the Land Gate, now accessed via Jehonatan HaHashmonai Street.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The walls then turn west along the city beach, reaching the sea's edge and turning south toward the fishing port and marina.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] At the former Sea Gate, now the Abu Christo restaurant, a seaside promenade begins, leading to the Flag Tower (Arabic: *Burj as-Sanjaq*), a bastion guarding the southwestern corner, home to the Acre lighthouse, built in 1912 on the south-western corner of the walls.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The walls then turn north, passing two defensive towers, *Burj al-Kishla* and *Al-Khadid Burj*, before returning to the Vineyard Tower.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Jazzar Pasha and his successor, Sulayman Pasha al-Adil, are both buried in a small graveyard adjacent to the mosque.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In a shrine on the second level of the mosque, a single hair from Muhammad's beard is kept and shown on special ceremonial occasions.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Built in 1795 by Jazzar Pasha, Acre's Turkish bath, south of the citadel, has a series of hot rooms and a hexagonal steam room with a marble fountain.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] It was used by the Irgun as a bridge to break into the citadel's prison.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The bathhouse kept functioning until 1950 and has housed a museum since 1954.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The building features marble floors, tiled walls, and colored glass in the domed roof, supported by four marble columns.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In the northern part of the Old City stands the citadel, built between 1775 and 1805 by Jazzar Pasha on the foundations of an older Crusader fortress.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The current building is an Ottoman fortification, built on the foundation of the citadel of the Knights Hospitaller.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The citadel was part of the city's defensive formation, reinforcing the northern wall.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] There, the citadel integrates with the defensive walls at the Treasury Tower (Arabic: *Burj al-Hazana*), with a view of the Old City and Haifa Bay.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] East of the tower, a Crusader-era garden has been recreated in front of the Visitor Center entrance.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The citadel features two inner courtyards, measuring 170 meters east to west and about 100 meters wide.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] During the 20th century the citadel was used mainly as Acre Prison and as the site for a gallows.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] During the Palestinian mandate period, activists of Arab nationalist and the Jewish Zionist movements were held prisoner there; some were executed there.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Today, the citadel's primary attraction is the Museum of Underground Prisoners, dedicated to the Jewish resistance during the Mandatory Palestine.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Exhibits include artifacts from nine executed Jewish fighters and a prison gallows.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] One display is a model depicting a 1947 prisoner escape.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Adjacent is the Okashi Art Museum, showcasing works by Israeli painter Absalom Okashi.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] This complex was a part of the Hospitallers citadel, which was included in the northern defences of Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The complex includes six semi-joined halls, one recently excavated large hall, a dungeon, a refectory (dining room) and remains of a Gothic church.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The old saraya lies south of the citadel, a two-story structure with an open, paved rectangular courtyard.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Built in the 18th century on the ruins of the Church of St.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] John the Baptist, it served as Jazzar Pasha's private residence.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] After he constructed a new palace, the serai housed civil administrative offices.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In the early 19th century, Ibrahim Pasha used it as a treasury, and it later became the governor's residence.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The Jewish community maintains two synagogues in Acre: the Ramchal Synagogue and the Or Torah Synagogue.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The Ramchal Synagogue, located in the heart of the Old City, is named after Rabbi Ramchal, who lived in Acre from 1743 to 1747.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In 1758, Bedouin ruler Daher al-Umar seized it, converting it into the al-Mu'allaq Mosque.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] As compensation, the Jewish community received a small building north of the mosque.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In the early 21st century, the synagogue was renovated and opened to tourists.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Near the Old City's outer walls is the Tunisian Synagogue, also known as Or Torah.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Legend claims that after the Second Temple's destruction in 70 CE, priests arrived in Acre, founding the El-Zaira Jewish quarter and placing salvaged Temple doors in the synagogue.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Christian churches are mostly concentrated in the southwestern part of Acre's Old City.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Historical records and 13th-century maps indicate that the Carmelites had a church near the sea.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] After the Crusaders left in 1291, the Carmelites departed, returning in the early 17th century to reestablish a church.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Acre holds significance for the Franciscans, who believe their founder, Francis of Assisi, visited between 1219 and 1220.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In 1217, Father Elia Da Cortona founded the first Franciscan monastery there.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] After Muslim conquest, the Franciscans fled, returning in 1620 to establish the Terra Sancta Church, the only church in the eastern Old City.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Saint George Greek Orthodox Cathedral, built before 1631 in the Greek Orthodox tradition, is considered the oldest Christian church in Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Further south are the Maronite Church, the Carmelite church and monastery dedicated to the Dome of Nazareth, and a second Greek Orthodox church, Church of Saint Andrew.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Near the lighthouse stands Saint John the Baptist Church, a Franciscan church built in 1737 and renovated in 1947, the only active Roman Catholic church in Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Among the sacred sites in Acre's Old City, Muslim mosques are the most numerous.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The oldest, the El-Bahr Mosque, built in 1586, lies in the southeastern part near the port, historically encompassing a bathhouse, café, warehouses, and shops.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The most prominent is the El-Jazzar Mosque, built in 1781 near the citadel and old saraya.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Its green dome and tall, slender minaret are visible across the Old City.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] It is Israel's largest mosque outside Jerusalem and the largest built in Palestine during Ottoman rule.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] South of the citadel, the Az-Zaytuna Mosque features two green domes and a tall minaret, reportedly built on the site of a Crusader-era Church of St.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Adjacent to the citadel's west side is the Ash-Shadhiliyya Mosque, renovated in the early 21st century and home to a dervish brotherhood.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Further west is the Al-Majadala Mosque, built in 1809.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In the central Old City are the Al-Muallaq Mosque and, further east, the Ar-Raml Mosque.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Several historic caravanserais, once hosting merchant caravans, are preserved in the Old City.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The Khan al-Umdan, built in 1785 near the port, featured a courtyard for unloading goods, with warehouses and an inn on the ground floor and a hotel upstairs.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Its courtyard is adorned with granite columns from Roman Caesarea.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In 1906, an Ottoman clock tower was added, with views of the port.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] About 30 meters west, the Khan ash-Shuna is neglected but it has original Crusader structures on its ground floor.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In the city center, the Khan al-Ifranj, the oldest fully preserved caravanserai, was built in the mid-16th century by French merchants, hence its name.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Its northern and northeastern wings now house the Franciscan Terra Santa School.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In the eastern Old City, the Khan ash-Shawarda was likely built on the site of a former Poor Clares convent.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] During British Mandate rule, its inner courtyard was converted into a street.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The most famous bazaar in Acre is the Suq Al-Abiad (White Market), built in the mid-18th century.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] For over 150 years, it was the city's primary marketplace, originally housing 110 shops but now reduced to 64 due to war damage.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] This covered market street, about 100 meters long, features cafés and shops on both sides.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] South of the El-Jazzar Mosque is the Turkish Bazaar, built in the late 18th century and used as a market until 1948.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] This 100-meter-long commercial street has a cross-vaulted ceiling with rectangular openings for sunlight, now housing art and souvenir shops.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] A commercial street also spans Marco Polo, Benjamin Metudela, and Fahir ad-Din streets.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Acre was a vital maritime and fishing port.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The first port in Acre was established in the 6th century BCE at the Na'aman river's mouth, south of the current Old City.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In the 7th century, Arabs built a new port with a shipyard, serving as the main Muslim naval base against Byzantium.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In the 8th century, the port and shipyard were relocated north to Tyre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Neglected until the late 9th century, the port was rebuilt by Egyptians with fortified defenses.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] It gained prominence under Crusader rule but was neglected again until the late 17th century.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Today, it serves as a small fishing harbor and marina.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Other medieval European remains include the Church of Saint George and adjacent houses at the Genovese Square (called Kikar ha-Genovezim or Kikar Genoa in Hebrew).
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] There are many Baháʼí holy places in and around Acre.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] They originate from Baháʼu'lláh's imprisonment in the Citadel during Ottoman Rule.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] The final years of Baháʼu'lláh's life were spent in the Mansion of Bahjí, just outside Acre, even though he was still formally a prisoner of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Baháʼu'lláh died on 29 May 1892 in Bahjí, and the Shrine of Baháʼu'lláh is the most holy place for Baháʼís — their Qiblih, the location they face when saying their daily prayers.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] It contains the remains of Baháʼu'lláh and is near the spot where he died in the Mansion of Bahjí.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] Other Baháʼí sites in Acre are the House of ʻAbbúd (where Baháʼu'lláh and his family resided) and the House of ʻAbdu'lláh Páshá (where later ʻAbdu'l-Bahá resided with his family), and the Garden of Ridván where he spent the end of his life.
[src:arwad/acre-israel-p02] In 2008, the Baháʼí holy places in Acre and Haifa were added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:arwad/adimeh] Some of its resident's were displaced during the Syrian Civil War, and since the conflict's conclusion in December 2024 at least 146 people have returned to their homes.
[src:arwad/adimeh] This figure only includes IDPs and not refugees.
[src:arwad/adimeh] Near Adimeh, there is a Crusader castle called Burj al-Sabi.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] Abdera was founded by the Phoenicians as a trading colony.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] It later grew to prominence under the Roman Empire.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] Adra was the last stronghold of the Moors in Spain.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] In January 1492 it was here that the forces of Boabdil were defeated ending the power of the Moors in Spain.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] In the 16th century defensive walls were built to protect the settlement.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] Adra had a population of 25,412 inhabitants in 2020 (according to the municipal census published by the National Institute of Statistics).
[src:arwad/adra-spain] The percentage of foreign born residents was 5.2% in 2005.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] The majority of these residents originated from Morocco, making up 49% of the total.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] The percentage of people living in the urban centre of Adra has been slowly increasing.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] In 2017 it represented 80% of the total municipal population.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] Adra Museum: Visitors can spend their free time in the three exhibition halls of the museum, which show the cultural legacy of the Phoenician, Punic and Roman civilizations, and which educate and entertain at the same time.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] Important exhibitions of national prestige are periodically held here with success.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] The museum has a shop where archaeological reproductions can be bought.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] A nearby mill, El Molino del Lugar, built around 1814 and recently renovated, is the site of the ethnographic section of the museum.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] The Fair: Adra's fair is considered to be the second most important in the province of Almería and the population of Adra and countless visitors gather between September 5 and 10.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] The patron saint is la Virgen del Mar, who is taken out in a procession on September 8, while San Nicolás de Tolentino is celebrated on the 10th with a procession through el Barrio, the old town.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] April 25 is the day of San Marcos and is important to the farmers of Adra.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] It is an official festival of tourist interest in Andalucía.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] July 16 is the day of Our Lady of Mount Carmel, the patron saint of fishermen.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] Bazaars take place two Saturdays a month in a carpark which is beside the Sports Center and I.E.S Abdera School.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] Adra had a successful regional level football club, C.F.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] It is on the Ramsar list of Wetlands of International Importance.
[src:arwad/adra-spain] Although it is protected as a nature reserve, the surrounding land is used for intensive agriculture.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir is one of the major urban centres of Morocco.
[src:arwad/agadir] The commune of Agadir recorded a population of 501,797 in the 2024 Moroccan census.
[src:arwad/agadir] According to the 2004 census, there were 346,106 inhabitants in that year and the population of the Prefecture of Agadir-Ida Outanane was 487,954 inhabitants.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir is known for being the capital of Berber culture in Morocco.
[src:arwad/agadir] A majority of 58.3% of the population of Agadir speak Arabic as their native language, while a sizable minority of 40.7% natively speak Berber languages, including the native variety of Tachelhit.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir is also a place for many festivals related to Berber culture, such as Yennayer and Bujlood, as well as being the birthplace of many of the pillars of Shilha music, such as Izenzaren and Oudaden.
[src:arwad/agadir] It was the site of the 1911 Agadir Crisis that exposed tensions between France and Germany, foreshadowing World War I.
[src:arwad/agadir] The city was destroyed by an earthquake in 1960; it has been completely rebuilt with mandatory seismic standards.
[src:arwad/agadir] It is now the largest seaside resort in Morocco, where foreign tourists and many residents are attracted by an unusually mild year-round climate.
[src:arwad/agadir] Since 2010 it has been well served by low-cost flights and a motorway from Tangier.
[src:arwad/agadir] The mild winter climate (January average midday temperature 20.5 °C/69 °F) and good beaches have made it a major "winter sun" destination for northern Europeans.
[src:arwad/agadir] The name *Agadir* is a common Berber noun, meaning 'wall, enclosure, fortified building, citadel'.
[src:arwad/agadir] This noun is attested in most Berber languages.
[src:arwad/agadir] It may come from the Tuareg word *aǧādir* ('wall' or 'bank') or from Phoenician *gadir* ('wall' or 'fortress').
[src:arwad/agadir] The former word may also be a loanword from the latter.
[src:arwad/agadir] The Phoenician etymology, if correct, would be the same as that of Cádiz in Spain.
[src:arwad/agadir] There are many more towns in Morocco called Agadir.
[src:arwad/agadir] The city of Agadir's full name in Tashelhit is *Agadir Ighir* or *Agadir-n-Irir*, literally 'the fortress of the cape', referring to the nearby promontory named Cape Ighir on maps (a pleonastic name, literally 'Cape Cape').
[src:arwad/agadir] The oldest known map that includes an indication of Agadir is from 1325: at the approximate location of the modern city, it names a place it calls *Porto Mesegina*, after a Berber tribe name that had been recorded as early as the 12th century, the *Mesguina* (also known as the *Ksima*).
[src:arwad/agadir] At the end of the medieval period, Agadir was a town of some renown.
[src:arwad/agadir] The first known mention of its name, *Agadir al-harba*, was recorded in 1510.
[src:arwad/agadir] In the late 15th century the Portuguese began to occupy positions along the Moroccan coast.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1505 the Portuguese nobleman João Lopes de Sequeira occupied the area.
[src:arwad/agadir] He built a wooden castle at the foot of a hill, near a spring, and a Portuguese colony named *Santa Cruz do Cabo do Gué* was created.
[src:arwad/agadir] The site still bears the name of Funti or Founti (from the Portuguese word *fonte,* meaning "fountain").
[src:arwad/agadir] The castle was later bought by the King of Portugal on 25 January 1513.
[src:arwad/agadir] The Portuguese presence elicited growing hostility from the local population of the Sous region, who initiated a years-long economic and military blockade of the port.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1510 Muhammad al-Qa'im, the leader of a Sharifian family that had established themselves in the Sous, was declared leader of the local military efforts against the Sous.
[src:arwad/agadir] His descendants went on to found the Sa'di dynasty which rose to power over the following decades and eventually established their capital at Marrakesh.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1540 the Sa'di sultan Muhammad al-Shaykh occupied the main hill (now Agadir Oufla) above the Portuguese and installed artillery to prepare an attack on the fortress below.
[src:arwad/agadir] The siege of the colony began on 16 February 1541 and was successfully concluded on 12 March of the same year.
[src:arwad/agadir] Six hundred Portuguese survivors were taken prisoner, including the governor, Guterre de Monroy, and his daughter, Dona Mecia.
[src:arwad/agadir] The captives were redeemed by the holy men, who were mostly from Portugal.
[src:arwad/agadir] Dona Mecia, whose husband was killed during the battle, became the wife of Sheikh Mohammed ash-Sheikh but died in childbirth in 1544.
[src:arwad/agadir] In the same year, Mohammed ash-Sheikh released Guterre de Monroy, whom he had befriended.
[src:arwad/agadir] After this, the Portuguese were forced to abandon most of the Moroccan areas that they had acquired control of between 1505 and 1520, including Agadir, Safi and Azemmour.
[src:arwad/agadir] By 1550, Portugal's only holding in Morocco was Mazagan (now El Jadida), Tangier and Ceuta.
[src:arwad/agadir] Following defeat in Morocco, the Portuguese turned their attention to India and Brazil, nations that they had more success pacifying.
[src:arwad/agadir] "Santa Cruz do Cabo de Gue d'Agoa de Narba – Estudo e Crónica", Joao Marinho e Santos, José Manuel Azevedo e Silva e Mohammed Nadir, bilingual edition, Viseu 2007).
[src:arwad/agadir] After the Sa'di victory the site was then left unoccupied for years until Muhammad al-Shaykh's successor, Abdallah al-Ghalib (r.
[src:arwad/agadir] 1557–1574), built a new fortress (or kasbah) on the hilltop.
[src:arwad/agadir] It was now called *Agadir N'Ighir* (literally: "fortified granary of the hill" in Tachelhit.
[src:arwad/agadir] In the 17th century, during the reign of the Berber dynasty of Tazerwalt, Agadir was a harbour of some importance, expanding its trade with Europe.
[src:arwad/agadir] There was, however, neither a real port nor a wharf.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir traded mainly in sugar, wax, copper, hides and skins.
[src:arwad/agadir] In exchange, Europeans sold their manufactured goods there, particularly weapons and textiles.
[src:arwad/agadir] Under the reign of Sultan Moulay Ismail (1645–1727) and his successors, the trade with France, which had previously been an active partner, diminished, and trade with the English and Dutch increased.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1731, the town was completely destroyed by an earthquake.
[src:arwad/agadir] After that, Agadir's harbour was ordered to be closed, and an alternative, Essaouira, was established farther north.
[src:arwad/agadir] After a long period of prosperity during the reigns of the Saadian and Alawite dynasties, Agadir declined from 1760 because of the pre-eminence given to the competing port of Essaouira by the Alawite Sultan Mohammed ben Abdallah who wanted to punish the Souss for rebelling against his authority.
[src:arwad/agadir] This decline lasted a century and a half.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1789, a European traveler gave a brief description of Agadir: "It is now a ghost town, there are no more than a few houses and these are crumbling into ruins".
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1881, Sultan Hassan I reopened the harbour to trade in order to supply the expeditions he planned in the south.
[src:arwad/agadir] These expeditions, which were to reassert his authority over the Souss tribes and counter the plans of English and Spanish, were held in 1882 and 1886.
[src:arwad/agadir] On the pretext of a call for help from German companies in the valley of the Souss, Germany decided on 1 July 1911, to extend its interests in Morocco and assert a claim on the country.
[src:arwad/agadir] It sent to the bay of Agadir, (whose harbour was, until 1881, closed to foreign trade) the SMS *Panther* which was quickly joined by the cruiser *Berlin*.
[src:arwad/agadir] Very strong international reaction, particularly from Great Britain, surprised Germany and triggered the Agadir Crisis between France and Germany.
[src:arwad/agadir] After tough negotiations, a Franco-German treaty was finally signed on 4 November 1911, giving a free hand to France, who would be able to establish its protectorate over Morocco in return for giving up some colonies in Africa.
[src:arwad/agadir] It was only then that the gunboat *Panther* and the cruiser *Berlin* left the bay of Agadir.
[src:arwad/agadir] Due to a miscalculation, the German sales representative Hermann Wilberg, who was sent to provide the pretext for the intervention, only arrived at Agadir three days after the *Panther* arrived.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1913, the cities (Agadir N'Ighir and Founti) totaled less than a thousand inhabitants.
[src:arwad/agadir] On 15 June 1913 French troops landed in Agadir.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1916, the first pier was built near Founti – a simple jetty, later known as the "Portuguese jetty", which remained until the end of the 20th century.
[src:arwad/agadir] After 1920, under the French protectorate, a port was built and the city saw its first development with the construction of the old Talborjt district located on the plateau at the foot of the hill.
[src:arwad/agadir] Two years later, beside Talborjt along the fault line of the river Tildi construction of the popular district of Yahchech began.
[src:arwad/agadir] Around 1930, Agadir was an important stop for the French airmail service Aéropostale and was frequented by Saint-Exupéry and Mermoz.
[src:arwad/agadir] From 1930 onwards, a modern central city began to be built according to the plans of the urban planner Henri Prost, director of the Protectorate's Urban Planning Department, and his deputy Albert Laprade.
[src:arwad/agadir] The design featured a horseshoe layout centred on a large avenue perpendicular to the waterfront – the Avenue Lyautey, since renamed Avenue du Général Kettani.
[src:arwad/agadir] In the 1950s, urban development continued under the direction of the Director of Urban Planning Morocco, Michel Ecochard.
[src:arwad/agadir] After 1950 and the opening of the new commercial port, the city grew with fishing, canning, agriculture, and mining.
[src:arwad/agadir] It also began to open up to tourism due to its climate and hotel infrastructure.
[src:arwad/agadir] Several years later from 1950 to 1956 Agadir organized the Grand Prix of Agadir and, from 1954 to 1956, the Moroccan Grand Prix.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1959, the port was visited by the yacht of the Greek shipping magnate Aristotle Onassis and his guest, Winston Churchill.
[src:arwad/agadir] By 1960, Agadir numbered over 40,000 residents when at 15 minutes to midnight on 29 February 1960, it was again almost totally destroyed by an earthquake of magnitude 5.7 on the Richter scale that lasted 15 seconds, burying the city and killing more than a third of the population.
[src:arwad/agadir] The earthquake destroyed the old Kasbah.
[src:arwad/agadir] The current city was rebuilt 1.6 kilometres (1 mi) further south, led by the architects associated with GAMMA, including Jean-François Zevaco, Elie Azagury, Pierre Coldefy, and Claude Verdugo, with consultation from Le Corbusier.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir became a large city of over half a million by 2004, with a large port with four basins: the commercial port with a draft of 17 metres, triangle fishing, fishing port, and a pleasure boat port with marina.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir was the premier sardine port in the world in the 1980s and has a beach stretching over 10 km with fine seafront promenades.
[src:arwad/agadir] Its climate has 340 days of sunshine per year which allows for swimming all year round.
[src:arwad/agadir] The winter is warm and in summer, haze is common.
[src:arwad/agadir] With Marrakech, Agadir is a very important centre for tourism to Morocco, and the city is the most important fishing port in the country.
[src:arwad/agadir] Business is also booming with the export of citrus fruit and vegetables produced in the fertile valley of Souss.
[src:arwad/agadir] On 12 December 2022, an earthquake of magnitude 4.5 hit Agadir Province.
[src:arwad/agadir] The earthquake struck at a depth of three kilometres beneath the epicentre, off the coast of Agadir.
[src:arwad/agadir] This area is named after the old district of Talborjt (meaning "small fort" in local Berber, in remembrance of the water tower which was first built on the plateau in the former Talborjt).
[src:arwad/agadir] Lively, the New Talborjt which has been rebuilt away from the Old Talborjt, has as the main artery the Boulevard Mohammed Sheikh Saadi, named after the victor against the Portuguese in 1541.
[src:arwad/agadir] Other major avenues are the Avenue President Kennedy and the Avenue 29 February.
[src:arwad/agadir] There is also the Mohammed V mosque, the Olhão garden (Olhão is a coastal city in southern Portugal that is twinned with Agadir), and its memorial museum and the Garden Ibn Zaydoun.
[src:arwad/agadir] Some good hotels and restaurants have been built on the main arteries.
[src:arwad/agadir] The K*asbah* (*Agadir Oufla*, *Agadir le haut*, *Agadir N'Ighir*, or *Agadir de la colline*) was, along with Founti by the sea, the oldest district of Agadir.
[src:arwad/agadir] An authentic fortress with winding streets and lively, the Kasbah was built in 1572 by Abdallah al-Ghalib.
[src:arwad/agadir] Of this fortress there remains, after the earthquake of 29 February 1960, a restored long high wall that surrounds land that is not buildable.
[src:arwad/agadir] There is, however, a view over the bay of Agadir and the ports.
[src:arwad/agadir] The old people of Agadir remember the "Moorish café" of the Kasbah and its panoramic view.
[src:arwad/agadir] The hill bears the inscription in Arabic: "God, Country, King" which, like the walls, is illuminated at night.
[src:arwad/agadir] Overlooking the waterfront and Wadi Tildi, this old district (whose name is sometimes spelled *Talbordjt*) was once a shopping area and very lively with its large square where there was a weekly market, hotels, schools, mosque.
[src:arwad/agadir] 90% of the buildings in Old Talborjt were destroyed or severely damaged by the earthquake in 1960.
[src:arwad/agadir] Razed to the ground after the earthquake and now overgrown, it is classified as non-buildable area.
[src:arwad/agadir] Its main thoroughfare, the Avenue El Moun stretches over 2 kilometres (1.2 mi) and serves only for driving schools that teach their students to drive.
[src:arwad/agadir] This is the largest market in the region.
[src:arwad/agadir] It is surrounded by walls and has several entrances.
[src:arwad/agadir] It is organized into different sectors: furniture, crafts, clothing, vegetables, meat, spices etc.
[src:arwad/agadir] It is possible to find all kinds of handicrafts and traditional decorations.
[src:arwad/agadir] The walls have been restored and the interior design is being finished.
[src:arwad/agadir] The prefecture is divided administratively into communes.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir has a semi-arid climate (Köppen: *BSh*) with warm summers and mild winters.
[src:arwad/agadir] Located along the Atlantic Ocean, Agadir has a very mild climate.
[src:arwad/agadir] The daytime temperature generally stays in the 20s °C (70s °F) every day with averages around 27 °C (81 °F), with the winter highs typically reaching 21 °C (70 °F) in January.
[src:arwad/agadir] Rainfall is almost entirely confined to the winter months and is heavily influenced by the NAO, with negative NAO indices producing wet winters and positive NAO correlating with drought.
[src:arwad/agadir] For instance, in the wettest month on record of December 1963, as much as 314.7 millimetres or 12.39 inches fell, whereas in the positive NAO year from July 1960 to June 1961 a mere 46.7 millimetres or 1.84 inches occurred over the twelve months.
[src:arwad/agadir] The wettest year has been from July 1955 to June 1956 with 455.5 millimetres or 17.93 inches.
[src:arwad/agadir] Occasionally however, the region experiences winds from the Sahara called *Chergui*, which may exceptionally and for two to five days raise the heat above 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:arwad/agadir] The confirmed record high temperature was 50.4 °C (122.7 °F) set on 12 August 2023.
[src:arwad/agadir] This makes Agadir one of few coastal locations in the world to have recorded a temperature above 50 °C.
[src:arwad/agadir] The record of 51.7 °C degrees, which was on 19 August 1940, is disputed.
[src:arwad/agadir] In 1950, a poster from the Navigation Company Pacquet proclaimed: "Winter or summer, I bathe in Agadir".
[src:arwad/agadir] The city had an annual growth rate of over 6% per year in housing demand while housing production barely exceeds 3.4%.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir's economy relies mainly on tourism and fisheries.
[src:arwad/agadir] Car rental services support the tourism sector by allowing visitors to reach nearby attractions such as Taghazout, Taroudant, and the Souss-Massa National Park.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agricultural activities are based around the city.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir has one of the biggest souks in Morocco (Souk El Had).
[src:arwad/agadir] The fishing port is a major sardine port.
[src:arwad/agadir] The commercial port is also known for its exports of cobalt, manganese, zinc and citrus products.
[src:arwad/agadir] The Avenue du Port, the main artery of the Anza district, is surrounded by canneries and has many popular small restaurants adjacent to the fish market.
[src:arwad/agadir] The city has a cement company called Ciments du Maroc (CIMAR), a subsidiary of the Italian group Italcementi which is in process of being transferred to a new plant 40 kilometres (25 mi) from the city.
[src:arwad/agadir] There is also a shipyard in the port and the only merchant marine school in Morocco.
[src:arwad/agadir] Agadir is served by Al Massira Airport, 23 kilometres (14 mi) from the city.
[src:arwad/agadir] About 22.9% of the population are under 15 years old, and 13.4% are over 60.
[src:arwad/agadir] Linguistically, a majority of 58.3% the population of Agadir speak Arabic as their native language, while a sizable minority of 40.7% natively speak Berber languages.
[src:arwad/agadir] The Timitar festival, a festival of Amazigh culture and music from around the world, has been held in Agadir every summer since its inception in July 2004.
[src:arwad/agadir] The *Morocco Movement* association is involved in the arts and organizes concerts, exhibitions and meetings in the visual arts, design, music, graphic design, photography, environment and health.
[src:arwad/agadir] The city of Agadir has a university: the Université Ibn Zohr which includes a Faculty of Science, Faculty of Medicine and Pharmacy, Faculty of Law, Economics and Social Sciences & the Faculty of Arts and Humanities.
[src:arwad/agadir] There is an international French school: the French School of Agadir and also public schools: Youssef Ben Tachfine School, Mohammed Reda-Slaoui School, and the Al-Idrissi Technical College.
[src:arwad/agadir] The city of Agadir has a football club known as Hassania Agadir and the city has built the new Adrar Stadium, which the team plays its home matches at.
[src:arwad/agadir] The city also hosts the Royal Tennis Club of Agadir.
[src:arwad/agadir] It could host matches in the 2030 FIFA World Cup.
[src:arwad/agadir] The Hassan II Golf Trophy and Lalla Meryem Cup golf tournaments of the European Tour and Ladies European Tour are held at the Golf du Palais Royal in Agadir since 2011.
[src:arwad/agadir] Some of the most popular beaches in Morocco are located to the north of Agadir.
[src:arwad/agadir] Areas known for surfing are located near Taghazout village to Cap Ghir.
[src:arwad/agadir] Many smaller and clean beaches are located along this coast.
[src:arwad/agadir] Some of them between Agadir and Essaouira are: Agadir Beach, Tamaounza (12 km), Aitswal Beach, Imouran (17 km), Taghazout (19 km), Bouyirdn (20 km), Timzguida (22 km), Aghroud (30 km), Imiouadar (27 km).
[src:arwad/agadir] *Ighir* (pronounced *irrhir*) later meaning shoulder or height.
[src:arwad/arwad] According to the Syria Central Bureau of Statistics, during the 2004 census, it had a population of 4,403, predominantly Arab Sunni Muslims.
[src:arwad/arwad] Plans were unveiled in May 2016 to renovate the island to become a tourist attraction.
[src:arwad/arwad] The island is currently surrounded by ancient Phoenician era walls.
[src:arwad/arwad] The original Phoenician city was named **Arwad** Phoenician: 𐤀𐤓𐤅𐤃‎, romanized: *ʾrwd* and was located on an island named (𐤀𐤉𐤍𐤊‎, *ʾynk*).
[src:arwad/arwad] It is mentioned in the Annals of Thutmose III at the Karnak Temple as *jrtw*.
[src:arwad/arwad] It eventually became known as **Arvad**, **Arpad**, and **Arphad**.
[src:arwad/arwad] These were hellenized as *Árados* (Ancient Greek: Ἄραδος), which was Latinized as **Aradus**.
[src:arwad/arwad] Under the Seleucid Empire, Antiochus I renamed it Antioch after himself or the father of Seleucus the Great.
[src:arwad/arwad] It was distinguished from several other cities of that name as **Antioch** or **Antiochia in Pieria** (Ancient Greek: Ἀντιόχεια τῆς Πιερίας, romanized: *Antiókheia tês Pierías*).
[src:arwad/arwad] Its site was also known as **Ruad Island** and **Ile Rouad** under the French occupation and mandate from 1916 to 1945.
[src:arwad/arwad] Postage stamps were issued in 1916 in the latter name.
[src:arwad/arwad] Arwad has been continuously inhabited since at least the 3rd millennium BC. it was mentioned in the archive of the Royal Palace of Ebla, then at Alalakh.
[src:arwad/arwad] The island was settled in the early 2nd millennium BC by the Phoenicians.
[src:arwad/arwad] Located some 50 kilometres (31 mi) north of Tripoli, it was a barren rock covered with fortifications and houses several stories in height.
[src:arwad/arwad] The island was about 800 m long by 500 m wide, surrounded by a massive wall, and an artificial harbor was constructed on the east toward the mainland.
[src:arwad/arwad] It developed into a trading city in early times, as did most of the Phoenician cities on this coast.
[src:arwad/arwad] It had a powerful navy, and its ships are mentioned in the monuments of Egypt and Assyria.
[src:arwad/arwad] In the Bible, an "Arvad" is noted as the forefather of the "Arvadites", a Canaanite people.
[src:arwad/arwad] The Phoenicians collected rain water in cisterns and shipped fresh water to the island, eventually discovering an undersea freshwater spring nearby.
[src:arwad/arwad] The city of Arwad seems to have had a sort of hegemony over the northern Phoenician cities, from the mouth of the Orontes to the northern limits of Lebanon, something like that of Sidon in the south.
[src:arwad/arwad] It brought under its authority some of the neighboring cities on the mainland, such as Marat (present-day Amrit) and Sumur, the former nearly opposite the island and the latter some kilometers to the south.
[src:arwad/arwad] It had its own local dynasty and coinage, and some of the names of its kings have been recovered.
[src:arwad/arwad] Thutmose III of Egypt took it in his campaign in north Syria (1472 BC), and it is noticed in the campaigns of Ramesses II in the early part of the 13th century BC.
[src:arwad/arwad] It is also mentioned in the Amarna letters as being in league with the Amorites in their attacks on the Egyptian possessions in Syria.
[src:arwad/arwad] About 1200 BC or a little later, it was sacked by invaders from Asia Minor or the islands, as were most of the cities on the coast. but it recovered when they were driven back.
[src:arwad/arwad] Its maritime importance is indicated by the inscriptions of the Assyrian kings.
[src:arwad/arwad] 1020 BC) boasts that he sailed in the ships of Arwad.
[src:arwad/arwad] 876 BC) made it tributary, but it revolted and 200 men of Arwad were mentioned among the allies of Hadadezer of Aram Damascus at the Battle of Qarqar, when all Syria seems to have been in league against Shalmaneser III (c.
[src:arwad/arwad] At this time, the king of Arwad was Mattan Baal.
[src:arwad/arwad] It was afterward tributary to Tiglath-pileser III and Sennacherib; under Sennacherib, its king was Abd-Ilihit c.
[src:arwad/arwad] 664) compelled its king Yakinlu to submit and send one of his daughters to become a member of the royal harem.
[src:arwad/arwad] Under the Persians, Arwad was allowed to unite in a confederation with Sidon and Tyre, with a common council at Tripolis.
[src:arwad/arwad] The Book of Ezekiel refers to its seamen and soldiers in the service of Tyre.
[src:arwad/arwad] When Alexander the Great invaded Syria in 332 BC, the king of Arwad, Gerostratus, and his son Straton submitted to him without resistance and sent their navy to support his Siege of Tyre.
[src:arwad/arwad] It seems to have received the favor of the Seleucid kings of Syria and enjoyed the right of asylum for political refugees.
[src:arwad/arwad] It is mentioned in a rescript from Rome about 138 BC in connection with other cities and rulers of the East, to show favor to the Jews.
[src:arwad/arwad] This was after Rome had begun to interfere in the affairs of Judea and Syria and indicates that Arwad was still of considerable importance at that time.
[src:arwad/arwad] The city has been cited as one of the first known examples of a republic in the Levant region, in which the people, rather than a monarch, are described as sovereign.
[src:arwad/arwad] The island was important as a base for commercial ventures into the Orontes valley.
[src:arwad/arwad] Arwad inaugurated a new civic era in 259 BC, when its traditional royalty disappeared, and it became a free independent city within the Seleucid kingdom, during the reign of Antiochus II.
[src:arwad/arwad] In Roman times, Arwad fiercely resisted Mark Antony when he came to Syria to find money there.
[src:arwad/arwad] When the city refused to co-operate, it was besieged in 38 BC, then eventually surrendered, which marked the end of its independence in 34–35 BC.
[src:arwad/arwad] The city of Aradus, as it was then called, became a Christian bishopric.
[src:arwad/arwad] Athanasius reports that, under Roman Emperor Constantine the Great, Cymatius, the Chalcedonian bishop of Aradus and also of Antaradus (whose names indicate that they were neighbouring towns facing each other) was driven out by the Arians.
[src:arwad/arwad] At the First Council of Constantinople in 381, Mocimus appears as bishop of Aradus.
[src:arwad/arwad] At the time of the Council of Ephesus (431), some sources speak of a Musaeus as bishop of Aradus and Antaradus, while others mention only Aradus or only Antaradus.
[src:arwad/arwad] Alexander was at the Council of Chalcedon in 451 as bishop of Antaradus, Paulus as bishop of Aradus, while, at a synod held at Antioch shortly before, Paulus took part as bishop of both Aradus and Antaradus.
[src:arwad/arwad] In 458, Atticus signed, as bishop of Aradus, the letter of the bishops of the province of Phoenicia Prima to Byzantine Emperor Leo I the Thracian protesting about the murder of Proterius of Alexandria.
[src:arwad/arwad] Theodorus or Theodosius, who died in 518, is mentioned as bishop of Antaradus in a letter from the bishops of the province regarding Severus of Antioch that was read at a synod held by Patriarch Mennas of Constantinople.
[src:arwad/arwad] The acts of the Second Council of Constantinople in 553 were signed by Asyncretius as bishop of Aradus.
[src:arwad/arwad] At the time of the Crusades, Antaradus, by then called Tartus or Tortosa, was a Latin Church diocese, whose bishop also held the titles of Aradus and Maraclea (perhaps Rachlea).
[src:arwad/arwad] It was united to the see of Famagusta in Cyprus in 1295.
[src:arwad/arwad] No longer a residential bishopric, Aradus is today listed by the Catholic Church as a titular see.
[src:arwad/arwad] During the later part of the 13th century, in the time of the Crusades, the island of Ruad was used as a bridgehead or staging area by the Crusaders.
[src:arwad/arwad] It was the last piece of land that the Crusaders maintained in the Holy Land.
[src:arwad/arwad] The Crusaders had lost control of the mainland in 1291 (see Fall of Acre), and the dwindling Kingdom of Jerusalem had been relocated to the island of Cyprus.
[src:arwad/arwad] In early 1300, in an attempt to coordinate military operations with the Mongol leader Ghazan, the Cypriots prepared a land-based force of approximately 600 men: 300 under Amalric of Lusignan, son of Hugh III of Cyprus, and similar contingents from the Templars and Hospitallers.
[src:arwad/arwad] The men and their horses were ferried from Cyprus to a staging area on Ruad, from which they launched raids on Tortosa while awaiting Mongol reinforcements.
[src:arwad/arwad] When the Mongols failed to arrive, the majority of the Christian forces returned to Cyprus, though a garrison was left on Ruad which was manned by rotating groups of different Cypriot forces.
[src:arwad/arwad] Pope Clement V formally awarded ownership of the island to the Knights Templar, who (in 1302) maintained a garrison with 120 knights, 500 bowmen and 400 Syrian helpers, under the Templar Maréchal (Commander-in-Chief) Barthélemy de Quincy.
[src:arwad/arwad] In February 1301, the Mongols did arrive with a force of 60,000, but could do little else than engage in some raids around Syria.
[src:arwad/arwad] The Mongol leader Kutluqa stationed 20,000 horsemen in the Jordan Valley to protect Damascus, where a Mongol governor was installed.
[src:arwad/arwad] The Egyptian Mamluks, who had been systematically re-establishing control over Palestine and Syria, sought to take Ruad as well.
[src:arwad/arwad] A Mamluk fleet landed a force on the island, engaging in combat with the entrenched Templars, and then establishing a lengthy siege, culminating with the Fall of Ruad, and the Crusaders surrendering on September 26, 1302, following a promise of safe conduct.
[src:arwad/arwad] However, the promise was not honored: all the bowmen and Syrian helpers were killed, and the Templar knights were sent to Cairo prisons.
[src:arwad/arwad] During WWI, the island was occupied by the French navy on 1 September 1915, under the leadership of Admiral Louis Dartige du Fournet, including warships such as *Jauréguiberry*, *Jeanne d'Arc* and *D'Estrées*.
[src:arwad/arwad] Later on, Albert Trabaud was appointed as its governor.
[src:arwad/arwad] Afterwards, the island was bombed by the Ottomans in November 1917, but their attack was repulsed by French sailors.
[src:arwad/arwad] Under the French Mandate the dungeons of the fortress were used as a prison for those opposing French rule, as the captives' still-visible graffiti attest.
[src:arwad/arwad] In 1945, at the end of WWII, France wanted to preserve the island, hence started working to build a military base, in a geopolitical framework, to maintain a military position in the region, and to keep a cultural influence.
[src:arwad/arwad] But as a result of pressure from the United States, the island was ceded unconditionally to Syria at the end of 1945, a decision confirmed in 1946.
[src:arwad/arwad] During the later half of the 20th century and the 21st century, the island's economy became more reliant on tourism, fishing and boatbuilding.
[src:arwad/arwad] This tourism focused economy was greatly impacted by the Syrian Civil War, due to the decreased travel to Syria.
[src:arwad/arwad] However, there has been no conflict on the island during the war, and it has been controlled by government forces from the beginning of the war until the fall of the Assad regime on December 8, 2024.
[src:arwad/arwad] Despite this, at least 20 islanders have lost their life in the course of the war.
[src:arwad/arwad] The COVID-19 pandemic has also affected the island's economy, further weakening the tourism industry, with many local businesses losing potential tourist related income.
